{"title_page": "Bumble-Bee (livery)", "text_new": "{{short description|Livery used on New Zealand railway locomotives}}\n[[Image:DFT 7295 Dunedin.JPG|thumb|250px|DFT 7295 in [[Dunedin, New Zealand|Dunedin]] while wearing the Tranz Rail winged logo.]]\n'''Bumble-Bee''' was an informal term, promoted by the editors of NZ Railfan Magazine, for the Tranz Rail \"winged' logo. The logo was then replaced with \"'''TR'''\" sloping block letters, which most of the rest of the locdescribing a [[Rail transport in New Zealand|New Zealand railway]] [[locomotive]] [[livery]] (resulting from the combination of black and yellow in the colour scheme) found in common usage amongst the [[railfan]] community. The livery, first introduced in May 2001 to promote [[level crossing]] safety to replace the [[Cato Blue (livery)|Cato Blue livery]] and was initially trialed on [[Tranz Rail]] locomotive [[NZR DC class|DC 4323]], and over time was applied to numerous other locomotive classes up until 5 May 2004, when [[Toll Domestic Forwarding|Toll Rail]] took over the rail system, and introduced the [[Corn-Cob (livery)|Corn-Cob livery]].<ref name=\"Railfan June 2001\">{{cite journal|title=New Zealand Railfan|publisher=Triple M Publications|volume=7|number=3|ISSN=1173-2229|date=June 2001}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:DFT7145_Ahuriri_8Jun2003_JChristianson.jpg|thumb|250px|DFT 7145 in [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]] while wearing the \"'''TR'''\" slopping blocks.]]\nThe first four locomotives that were painted in the livery received locomotives that were painted in the livery received, including DC 4323 and DFT 7160 which had received the livery with the Tranz Rail logo.<ref name=\"Railfan March 2002\">{{cite journal|title=New Zealand Railfan|publisher=Triple M Publications|volume=8|number=2|ISSN=1173-2229|date=March 2002}}</ref> DC 4185, DX 5166 and EF 30071 never received branding when they were repainted in the livery.<ref name=\"Railfan September 2001\">{{cite journal|title=New Zealand Railfan|publisher=Triple M Publications|volume=7|number=4|ISSN=1173-2229|date=September 2001}}</ref> DC 4185 initially didn't receive branding either when it was repainted, but the sloping block letters were later applied to the loco.<ref name=\"Railfan March 2004\"/>\n\nAs of September 2017, only two DCs, one [[New Zealand DSC class locomotive|DSC]] and three [[New Zealand EF class locomotive|EFs]] still operate in this livery.\n\n==Variations==\n\n[[Image:DSG 3251 Dunedin2.JPG|thumb|250px|DSG 3251 in [[Dunedin]].]]\nA few locomotives had been repainted in variations of this livery:\n*[[New Zealand DSC class locomotive|DSC 2678]] was repainted in the livery, but with a red stripe running down the sides of its hoods, which are the colours of [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]].<ref name=\"Railfan December 2002\">{{cite journal|title=New Zealand Railfan|publisher=Triple M Publications|volume=9|number=1|ISSN=1173-2229|date=December 2002}}</ref> \n*[[New Zealand DSG class locomotive|DSG 3251]] was repainted in the [[Otago]] colours of blue and yellow instead of black and yellow, with \"'''TR'''\" block letters on the logo hood, and a bumble-bee version of the Tranz Rail winged logo on the cab.<ref name=\"Railfan December 2002\" /> \n*[[New Zealand TR class locomotive|TR 874]] was repainted in this livery, but in reverse with a black cab and yellow hoods, with a bumble-bee version of the Tranz Rail winged logo also painted on the long hood. This variation was called by many rail enthusiasts as the \"Wasp\" livery.<ref name=\"Railfan September 2002\">{{cite journal|title=New Zealand Railfan|publisher=Triple M Publications|volume=8|number=4|ISSN=1173-2229|date=September 2002}}</ref>\n*Although not an official variation, [[New Zealand DC class locomotive|DC]]s 4421 and 4853 have received KiwiRail stickers on the front of the short-hood, and back of the long-hood.\n\n==Locomotives that wore/wear the Bumble Bee livery==\n[[New Zealand DC class locomotive|DC class]]:\n*4012<ref name=\"Railfan June 2002\">{{cite journal|title=New Zealand Railfan|publisher=Triple M Publications|volume=8|number=3|ISSN=1173-2229|date=June 2002}}</ref> - now in the [[KiwiRail]] Bold livery<ref name=\"Railfan June 2011\">{{cite journal|title=Railfan|publisher=Triple M Publications|volume=17|number=3|ISSN=1173-2229|date=June 2011}}</ref>\n*4058<ref name=\"Railfan December 2002\" /> - now in the KiwiRail Bold livery<ref name=\"Railfan June 2011\" />\n*4185<ref name=\"Railfan September 2001\" /> - now stored at [[Hutt Workshops]]<ref name=\"Railfan December 2016\">{{cite journal|title=Railfan|publisher=Triple M Publications|volume=23|number=1|ISSN=1173-2229|date=December 2016}}</ref>\n*4300<ref name=\"Railfan September 2002\" /> - now scrapped\n*4317<ref name=\"Railfan September 2003\">{{cite journal|title=New Zealand Railfan|publisher=Triple M Publications|volume=9|number=4|ISSN=1173-2229|date=September 2003}}</ref> - now scrapped\n*4323<ref name=\"Railfan June 2001\" /> - now in the KiwiRail Bold livery<ref name=\"Railfan March 2011\">{{cite journal|title=Railfan|publisher=Triple M Publications|volume=17|number=2|ISSN=1173-2229|date=March 2011}}</ref>\n*4398<ref name=\"Railfan December 2002\" /> - now scrapped\n*4421<ref name=\"Railfan September 2001\" /> - now stored in Middleton Yard, [[Christchurch]]\n*4438<ref name=\"Railfan December 2002\" /> - now stored at [[Hillside Engineering|Hillside Workshops]]<ref name=\"Hillside OIA\">{{cite web |url=https://fyi.org.nz/request/4554-hillside#incoming-15120 |title=Hillside (Official Information Act request) |date=4 October 2016 |website=fyi.org.nz |publisher=KiwiRail |access-date=10 January 2018}}</ref>\n*4450<ref name=\"Railfan March 2003\" /> - repainted in the KiwiRail Bold livery<ref name=\"Railfan December 2011\">{{cite journal|title=Railfan|publisher=Triple M Publications|volume=18|number=1|ISSN=1173-2229|date=December 2011}}</ref> and now scrapped\n*4473<ref name=\"Railfan September 2002\" /> - now stored at Hillside Worksho